This paper is about dialogue state tracking (DST), which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). The paper proposes a new mechanism for more efficient DST, which involves predicting state operations and selectively overwriting memory. This mechanism involves machine learning techniques such as prediction and decomposition, which are commonly used in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions the use of neural networks, which is a subfield of both AI and machine learning. Additionally, the paper discusses the performance improvement of the proposed method, which is achieved through training and optimization, both of which are topics in neural networks (cs.NE) and system design (cs.SD).
